'''Neal Lane Johnson''', known as '''Lanny Johnson''' (born 1940), is a [[school superintendent]] in [[Winnsboro, Louisiana|Winnsboro]], [[Louisiana]], who served as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] in the [[Louisiana State Legislature|Louisiana House of Representatives]] from 1976-1980.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://house.louisiana.gov/H_PDFdocs/HouseMembers1812_2008.pdf|title=Membership in the Louisiana House of Representatives, 1812-2008|publisher=house.louisiana.gov|accessdate=December 30, 2009}}</ref>  Johnson filled the District 20 seat vacated by [[Lantz Womack]], a [[banker]] and [[farmer]] from Winnsboro, who ran unsuccessfully for state agriculture commissioner in the first-ever [[nonpartisan blanket primary]] held in Louisiana on November 1, 1975.<ref>State of Louisiana, Secretary of State, Election returns, November 1, 1975</ref> 

Four years later, Johnson ran unsuccessfully in the primary for the [[Louisiana State Legislature|Louisiana State Senate]]. The victor in the 1979 [[general election]] was his state House colleague, [[Dan Richey]], then of [[Ferriday, Louisiana|Ferriday]] in [[Concordia Parish, Louisiana|Concordia Parish]], a Democrat<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legis.state.la.us/members/s1880-2004.pdf|title=Membership in the Louisiana State Senate, 1880-2004|publisher=legis.state.la.us|accessdate=December 30, 2009}}</ref> who years later switched to [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] affiliation. Richey defeated  Mary Lou Winters of [[Columbia, Louisiana|Columbia]], the seat of [[Caldwell Parish, Louisiana|Caldwell Parish]], the then Democratic national committeewoman. A former House member, [[David I. Patten]], a contractor from [[Harrisonburg, Louisiana|Harrisonburg]], the seat of [[Catahoula Parish, Louisiana|Catahoula Parish]], also ran unsuccessfully in the senatorial primary.<ref>State of Louisiana, Election returns, 1979 primary and general election</ref>

From the 1970s-1984, Johnson, originally from [[Ouachita Parish, Louisiana|Ouachita Parish]], was a [[schoolteacher]], administrator, or superintendent for the [[Tensas Parish, Louisiana|Tensas Parish]] School Board in [[St. Joseph, Louisiana|St. Joseph]]. The Tensas superintendent now is his wife, the former Carol Shipp (born 1941), originally from Bosco, also in Ouachita Parish.<ref name=list>{{cite web|url=http://www.doe.state.la.us/lde/uploads/1920.pdf|title=Louisiana Public School Districts Superintendents|publisher=doe.state.la.us|accessdate=December 30, 2009}}</ref>

Johnson graduated from Ouachita Parish High School in [[Monroe, Louisiana|Monroe]] and at eighteen played [[basketball]] at the [[University of Louisiana at Monroe]], then Northeast Louisiana State College, under coach [[Lenny Fant]], who became a close friend and often supplied Johnson with humorous references for use in political speeches.<ref name=fant>{{cite web|url=http://www.bayou.com/~suelynn/obituaries/lofobit.html|title="Fant's legacy lives on 'in his boys'", ''[[Monroe News Star]], October 13, 1998|publisher=bayou.com|accessdate=January 1, 2009}}</ref> Johnson was ULM's first All-American.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bayou.com/~suelynn/obituaries/lofobit.html|title=Mark S. Rainwater, "Fant's legacy lives on in 'his boys'", October 13, 1998|publisher=''[[Monroe News Star]]''|accessdate=January 3, 2010}}</ref>Johnson led the Warhawks in 1961-1962 to a 17-8 record and to their first [[Gulf South Conference]] championship. In 1962, Johnson made both the [[Associated Press]] and [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics]] listings. Johnson led the GSC in scoring for his last two seasons at ULM. He produced eight 30-point games and concluded his career with ULM<U+2019>s all-time scoring record with 1,366 points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ulmwarhawks.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=19000&ATCLID=3758997|title=Lanny Johnson|publisher=ulmwarhawks.com|accessdate=January 7, 2010}}</ref>Johnson also holds a [[Ph.D.]] in education.<ref name=list/>  In 1982 he was inducted into the Louisiana Basketball Hall of Fame for his 1958<U+2013>1962 seasons at the [[University of Louisiana at Monroe]].<ref name="name">{{cite web |date= 2010 |url = http://members.cox.net/tigerdsl/labc/hoffmemberschrono.htm|title = Louisiana Basketball Hall of Fame Members|format = |publisher = Louisiana Basketball Hall of Fame| accessdate = January 9, 2010 | last= |quote=}}</ref>

From 1984-2004, Johnson was the superintendent of the [[Ouachita Parish, Louisiana|Ouachita Parish]] schools, distinct from the [[Monroe, Louisiana|Monroe]] city system.<ref name=fant/> In Ouachita Parish, he presided over a widespread school expansion program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coachesaid.com/Article/2009/8/30/Franklin-Parish-Football|title=2009 August 30 Franklin Parish Football|publisher=coachesaid.com|accessdate=December 30, 2009}}</ref> In 2004, he accepted the superintendency of the financially-troubled [[Franklin Parish, Louisiana|Franklin Parish]] schools, where he still serves from his office in Winnsboro.<ref name=list/> After the failure of several tax propositions, Johnson procured funding for construction and renovation of certain schools.<ref>"Tax renewals pass in two area parish elections", ''Monroe News Star'', November 15, 2009</ref> 

Lanny and Carol Johnson reside on [[Lake Bruin]] near St. Joseph. They have one son, Taylor Lance Johnson (born 1978).<ref>People Search and Background Check</ref>

